Plasma Fluid - Finite Difference Time Domain model (PF-FDTD)
version 1.8+
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

************************************************************************************
COMPILE:
 Verify that the following files are in a common directroy
	pffdtd.cpp	- main program
	plasma.h	- extension of fdtd to plasma equation 
	memallocate.h	- memory allocating subroutines (see 
			  Numerical Recipes in C)
	output.h	- output subroutines
	source.h	- source subroutines
	Retard.h	- Retarded Time Absorbing Boundary Conditions
			  (only applied to E)
	TubeBC.h	- Retard.h in a plasma tube along the z-axis
			  (must recompile in order to change BC)
 Compile: g++ pffdtd.cpp.
 Change name to pffdtd: mv pffdtd.cpp pffdtd

************************************************************************************
RUN:
 PFFDTD <input file> <output file> <plasma frequency> <collision frequency>
	<gyro frequency> <elevation angle of DC B> <azmith angle of DC B>
	<plasma tempurature>
All files will have the appropriate sufixes added to them by the program (i.e.
	input.str - Input file
	output.vc - Voltage / Current output file
	output.fd - Field Data output file 
If only the first two arguments are given, PFFDTD assumes a free space model
(i.e. no plasma).

************************************************************************************
INPUT FILE FORMAT
Grid Parameter is self explanitory

Source Parameter starts with the number of wanted sources.  Then each source 
starts with the grid corodinates followed by the field to be effected (1=x,2=y,3=z).
The source type and parameter are then specified (1=sine par=frequency, 2=pulse 
par=freq, 3=rased cosine par=freq, 4=gausinan par=spread, 5=gausinan direvitive
par=spread, 6=DC par=value, 7=Sinc par=cutoff frequency)

Dielectric perimitivity is then specified. Currently PF-FDTD can only take 2.

Antenna Structure starts with the number of cells. Then each cell is specifid by
it's location followed by the desired material (0=free space/plasma, 1=metal, 2=Er1,
3=Er2).

Output field info is used to specify the locations where the electric, magnetic,
velocity, and density values will be saved to <output file.fd>.  First the outputing
of fields must be turned on (1=on, 0=off).  Due to the possibility to create LARGE
output files, the number of iterations between outputs must be specitifed (the
larger this is the smaller the output file). The last two lines are then used to
specify the upper and lower limits of the area of intrest (All locations between
these two limits will be outputed)

//Name of File
//Grid Parameters
sx	sy	sz
dx	dy	dz
//Source Parameters
# of sources
x	y	z	field	type	par
.	.	.	.	.	.
.	.	.	.	.	.
.	.	.	.	.	.
//Dielectric Parameters
Er1
Er2
//Antenna Structure
# of cells
x	y	z	Erx	Ery	Erz	
.	.	.	.	.	.
.	.	.	.	.	.
.	.	.	.	.	.
//Output Field Info
#of iterations between outputs	E(0/1)	B	Ue	Ne	Ui	Ni
lower_x	lower_y	lower_z
upper_x	upper_y	upper_z

************************************************************************************
OUTPUT FILE FORMAT	
<*.vc> Specifies the voltage and current of each source listed in <input file>. The
first line is a reference line that can be used in data analysis. It specifies the 
source number and whether its voltage (X1) or current (X2).

Time	Source Number(voltage)	Source Number(current)	Source Number(Voltage) 	...
0	11			12			21			...
<VALUES BEGIN ON SECOND LINE>

<*.fd> Specifies the desired fields (Specified in <input file>). The first four
lines are use to aid in data analysis. The first identifies the type of field that
makes up the column (1X=Electric, 2X=Magnetic, 3X=Velocity, 4X=Density, X1=x-axis,
X2=y-axis, X3=z-axis). The second, third, and fourth lines are the location of the
value, (x,y,z) respecfully.

Time	Field Value 1	Field Value 2	...	Field Value N	...
0	11 (EX)		12 (EY)		...	32 (UY)		...
0	x		x		...	x		...
0	y		y		...	y		...
0	z		z		...	z		...
.	.		.		.	.		.
.	.		.		.	.		.
.	.		.		.	.		.

************************************************************************************
See dipole.str for sample input file.
See dipole.vc for sample voltage/current output file
See dipole.fd for sample field data output file

